    "abstract": [],
    "body_text": [
        {
            "text": "The aetiology of diarrhoea in the bovine animal is complex, and a variety of viruses have been associated with the syndrome. The purpose of the present report is to give serological evidence for an aetiological role of bovine coronavirus in an epizootic diarrhoea of adult cattle in Japan, with supportive electron-microscopical and cell culture studies.",
            "cite_spans": [],
            "ref_spans": [],
            "section": "INTRODUCTION"
        },
        {
            "text": "Herds concerned. In ten herds from central and western areas of Japan, 150 of 200 adult cows developed diarrhoea during the winter of 1976--1977. Milk production declined by an average 20% during the outbreak and for 3--4 weeks during recovery periods.",
            "cite_spans": [],
            "ref_spans": [],
            "section": "MATERIALS AND METHODS"
        },
        {
            "text": "Serology. Paired serum samples were taken during the acute and convalescent stages of the syndrome, and were tested for haemaggiutination-inhibiting (HI) or neutralizing (NT) antibodies again \u00a7t reference strains of bovine coronavirus (BVC) using techniques described by Sharpee et al. (1976) and Stair et al. (1972) , of calf rotavirus (NCDV, Fernelius et ai., 1972) , of bovine adenovirus type 7 (BAV-7 -- Inaba et al., 1968) , of parainfluenzavirus type 3 (PIV-3 -- Inaba et ah, 1963) and of bovine viral diarrhoea-mucosal disease virus (BVD-MD -- Omori et al. 1967 ).",
            "cite_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 271,
                    "end": 296,
                    "text": "Sharpee et al. (1976) and",
                    "ref_id": "BIBREF8"
                },
                {
                    "start": 297,
                    "end": 316,
                    "text": "Stair et al. (1972)",
                    "ref_id": "BIBREF9"
                },
                {
                    "start": 344,
                    "end": 367,
                    "text": "Fernelius et ai., 1972)",
                    "ref_id": null
                },
                {
                    "start": 408,
                    "end": 427,
                    "text": "Inaba et al., 1968)",
                    "ref_id": "BIBREF5"
                },
                {
                    "start": 469,
                    "end": 487,
                    "text": "Inaba et ah, 1963)",
                    "ref_id": null
                },
                {
                    "start": 551,
                    "end": 568,
                    "text": "Omori et al. 1967",
                    "ref_id": "BIBREF6"
                }
            ],
            "ref_spans": [],
            "section": "MATERIALS AND METHODS"
        },
        {
            "text": "Electron microscopy (EM). A faeces sample taken during the acute phase was homogenised at 5% v/v in phosphate buffered saline (PBS) at pH 7.2.",
            "cite_spans": [],
            "ref_spans": [],
            "section": "MATERIALS AND METHODS"
        },
        {
            "text": "The suspension was clarified by centrifugation at 5000 g for 20 min, and the supernatant fluid was again centrifuged at 20,000 g for 30 min. A final centrifugation of the resulting supernatant fluid was made at 100,000 g for 2 h, and the pellet was resuspended in 1/50 original volume of PBS, and clarified at 20,000 g for 10 min. A drop of the supernatant fluid was examined by the phosphotungstic acid negative staining technique.",
            "cite_spans": [],
            "ref_spans": [],
            "section": "MATERIALS AND METHODS"
        },
        {
            "text": "Virus isolation and immunofluorescence. Primary bovine kidney (BK) cell cultures were prepared in 100 X 11 mm tubes (Sato et al., 1978) , and monolayers were infected with 0.1 ml of faeces extract prepared as above. After an adsorption period of 2 h at 37\u00b0C, infected cultures were washed 3 X with Earle's solution, fed with 0.5 ml of maintenance medium, and incubated at 37\u00b0C in a roller drum. Cultures were routinely checked for immunofluorescence at each passage, using a rabbit antiserum to bovine coronavirus (kindly supplied by Dr. C.A. Mebus, Lincoln, Nebraska, U.S.A.) conjugated to fluorescein isothiocyanate as described by Sato et al. (1978) .",
            "cite_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 116,
                    "end": 135,
                    "text": "(Sato et al., 1978)",
                    "ref_id": "BIBREF7"
                },
                {
                    "start": 634,
                    "end": 652,
                    "text": "Sato et al. (1978)",
                    "ref_id": "BIBREF7"
                }
            ],
            "ref_spans": [],
            "section": "MATERIALS AND METHODS"
        },
        {
            "text": "Serial ten-fold dilutions of the supernatant fluids were passaged weekly to fresh BK monolayers which were checked for cytopathic effect and immuno-fluorescence. Table I , 59% of 100 paired sera showed significant seroconversion between acute and convalescent sera, as measured by the HI technique for antibody to BCV. Only a low percentage showed sero conversions to other viruses tested. Of 210 cattle tested for coronavirus antibody from 8 of the farms concerned, 139 (66.2%) showed levels of HI antibody to coronavirus greater than titre of 160 (Table I) .",
            "cite_spans": [],
            "ref_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 162,
                    "end": 169,
                    "text": "Table I",
                    "ref_id": null
                },
                {
                    "start": 549,
                    "end": 558,
                    "text": "(Table I)",
                    "ref_id": null
                }
            ],
            "section": "MATERIALS AND METHODS"
        },
        {
            "text": "From diarrhoea faeces of an affected cow, EM preparations revealed the presence of numerous particles 60 to 120 nm in diameter; with the morphology of coronaviruses (Fig.l) . Similar particles were observed in sucrose density gradient preparations (Sato et ah, 1978) of fluids from infected BK cultures.",
            "cite_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 248,
                    "end": 266,
                    "text": "(Sato et ah, 1978)",
                    "ref_id": null
                }
            ],
            "ref_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 165,
                    "end": 172,
                    "text": "(Fig.l)",
                    "ref_id": null
                }
            ],
            "section": "As shown in"
        },
        {
            "text": "No cytopathic effect (CPE) or convincing immuno-fluorescence was seen during the first passage in vitro of faeces extract. From the second to the eighth passage in vitro fluorescent cells increased in number, and from the eighth passage CPE became obvious, characterised by syncytia formation and granularity of cells. This CPE, which became more distinct on further passage, was neutralised by rabbit antiserum to bovine coronavirus. ",
            "cite_spans": [],
            "ref_spans": [],
            "section": "As shown in"
        },
        {
            "text": "Whilst there are numerous reports of coronavirus-like agents associated with calf diarrhoea (Stair et al., 1972 , Bridger et al., 1978 ), only Homer et al. (1976 and more recently Durham et al. (1979) have reported such viruses in association with diarrhoea in adult cattle. Whilst the evidence is suggestive that the coronavirus-like particles are active during the diarrhoea, it still remains to be proven that they are indeed the aetiological agent of such diarrhoea.",
            "cite_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 92,
                    "end": 111,
                    "text": "(Stair et al., 1972",
                    "ref_id": "BIBREF9"
                },
                {
                    "start": 112,
                    "end": 134,
                    "text": ", Bridger et al., 1978",
                    "ref_id": "BIBREF0"
                },
                {
                    "start": 135,
                    "end": 161,
                    "text": "), only Homer et al. (1976",
                    "ref_id": null
                },
                {
                    "start": 180,
                    "end": 200,
                    "text": "Durham et al. (1979)",
                    "ref_id": "BIBREF1"
                }
            ],
            "ref_spans": [],
            "section": "DISCUSSION"
        }
